1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:05,150 --> 00:00:06,750
Howdy-do, Marcelka.

3
00:00:07,750 --> 00:00:08,370
Tomas?

4
00:00:08,650 --> 00:00:09,870
I'm brushing up on my Moravian.

5
00:00:09,870 --> 00:00:10,510
But why?

6
00:00:10,850 --> 00:00:12,850
Because of the concert in Lidecko.

7
00:00:13,950 --> 00:00:17,650
So some Moravians won't start yelling, go home, you Prague snob.

8
00:00:17,850 --> 00:00:19,470
Like in Zlin.

9
00:00:20,950 --> 00:00:23,900
That was a great lesson, Marcelka, a great one.

10
00:00:24,350 --> 00:00:25,460
I'm glad.

11
00:00:25,950 --> 00:00:29,750
After all those years out of the business I forgot that Moravia takes preparation.

12
00:00:30,450 --> 00:00:34,350
So you don't look like a snob who doesn't know what goes on in the countryside.

13
00:00:35,650 --> 00:00:40,870
If you hadn't said "greetings, Gottwaldov" right at the start in Zlin, they would've let you sing.

14
00:00:43,350 --> 00:00:48,750
It happens, but in Lidecko they'll see I'm no dumb Prague guy.

15
00:00:49,350 --> 00:00:50,540
It's somewhere in Moravia, right?

16
00:00:50,950 --> 00:00:51,750
Near Vsetin.

17
00:00:52,150 --> 00:00:52,650
Isn't it?

18
00:00:53,160 --> 00:00:53,740
It is.

19
00:00:54,650 --> 00:00:55,800
Splendid.

20
00:00:56,150 --> 00:00:58,750
I want us to arrive as one of their own.

21
00:00:59,150 --> 00:01:03,550
So I'm not Tommy Paci from Prague for them, but one of them.

22
00:01:08,060 --> 00:01:08,840
So, what do you think?

23
00:01:09,550 --> 00:01:14,050
Do you still think someone there would dare yell, you damned Prague bastard?

24
00:01:16,550 --> 00:01:17,150
More like a hillbilly.

25
00:01:19,510 --> 00:01:19,950
What?

26
00:01:56,750 --> 00:01:58,750
I'm sorry, I must look like an idiot.

27
00:01:58,780 --> 00:02:00,080
Don't worry about it.

28
00:02:00,080 --> 00:02:02,650
You're just not an expert on folk costumes.

29
00:02:02,870 --> 00:02:04,450
But they messed it up at the rental shop.

30
00:02:05,090 --> 00:02:07,130
I specifically wanted the one Kozina wore.

31
00:02:08,800 --> 00:02:09,240
Bro!

32
00:02:09,750 --> 00:02:11,410
Bro, you gotta come with me to the Badger right now.

33
00:02:11,950 --> 00:02:14,190
He got stuck there, it's dangerous, they're demolishing.

34
00:02:14,350 --> 00:02:15,770
Exactly, Milos is still in there.

35
00:02:16,190 --> 00:02:16,630
Oh God.

36
00:02:17,040 --> 00:02:17,940
I have to save him.

37
00:02:18,040 --> 00:02:18,560
Call 112.

38
00:02:19,080 --> 00:02:19,980
Calm down, Marcelka.

39
00:02:20,100 --> 00:02:22,160
Tomas, even a drunk is a human being.

40
00:02:22,420 --> 00:02:25,820
Milos is the stuffed badger that Simona had by the tap.

41
00:02:27,400 --> 00:02:28,260
Calm down, bro.

42
00:02:28,320 --> 00:02:29,160
What would you even do with it?

43
00:02:29,420 --> 00:02:30,080
A monument.

44
00:02:30,450 --> 00:02:32,180
So people don't forget a good pub.

45
00:02:32,180 --> 00:02:32,280
What?

46
00:02:33,100 --> 00:02:35,760
Horvat already found me a primo pedestal at Petrin.

47
00:02:35,880 --> 00:02:37,020
Didn't even want anything for it.

48
00:02:37,160 --> 00:02:40,600
Because he got three kilos at the scrap yard for the guy with a bouquet that was bolted to it.

49
00:02:42,750 --> 00:02:43,950
Get it, bro?

50
00:02:44,050 --> 00:02:46,720
We'll put him right in front of the entrance and he'll stand there forever.

51
00:02:46,750 --> 00:02:48,450
Like that tank in Smichov!

52
00:02:48,650 --> 00:02:51,050
The tank in Smichov has been gone for ages.

53
00:02:52,100 --> 00:02:52,580
What?

54
00:02:55,830 --> 00:02:58,910
Marcelka, we clearly agreed you'd be sensitive around him for a while.

55
00:02:58,910 --> 00:03:00,670
But I don't understand why the tank is so great.

56
00:03:00,690 --> 00:03:03,110
It should've been hidden away at the reservists' for harder times.

57
00:03:06,750 --> 00:03:11,250
Mr. Ozzak, Milos wouldn't have lasted long in fresh air anyway.

58
00:03:13,150 --> 00:03:15,350
It's true he liked it when it was really smoky.

59
00:03:15,350 --> 00:03:16,890
He'd fall apart in no time.

60
00:03:16,910 --> 00:03:18,170
He was full of dust mites.

61
00:03:22,540 --> 00:03:24,040
You're doing that on purpose, aren't you?

62
00:03:24,160 --> 00:03:25,160
Doing what, for God's sake?

63
00:03:25,340 --> 00:03:28,960
Don't you understand that if you say "dust mites" in front of Ozzak, he'll remember he's got no beer on tap anywhere?

64
00:03:29,220 --> 00:03:32,160
You know, it's like with Zoran, when you say Yugoslavia in front of him.

65
00:03:33,550 --> 00:03:34,550
Mr. Ozzak!

66
00:03:34,550 --> 00:03:37,450
Relax, Marcelka, Ozzak's sadness never lasts long.

67
00:03:37,650 --> 00:03:40,490
Right, I'm heading to Marik's place.

68
00:03:40,490 --> 00:03:42,950
It's my first time there, so if they baptize me, we might start late.

69
00:03:43,270 --> 00:03:44,470
It could take a while.

70
00:03:44,610 --> 00:03:45,070
Sure.

71
00:03:46,250 --> 00:03:47,250
Cool, a hockey stick.

72
00:04:02,750 --> 00:04:06,950
Little maid from Lidecko, my dear.

73
00:04:07,150 --> 00:04:11,550
Little maid from Lidecko kept on dancing.

74
00:04:15,450 --> 00:04:16,150
Iva, Iva!

75
00:04:20,020 --> 00:04:20,580
What?

76
00:04:22,950 --> 00:04:24,050
I'm composing.

77
00:04:24,230 --> 00:04:24,990
Right, I see.

78
00:04:27,550 --> 00:04:29,710
Sorry, I'll finish vacuuming later then.

79
00:04:29,710 --> 00:04:32,590
How's it going?

80
00:04:33,450 --> 00:04:34,050
Slowly.

81
00:04:35,750 --> 00:04:36,780
Can I do the dishes?

82
00:04:36,950 --> 00:04:38,450
Are there any pots?

83
00:04:38,950 --> 00:04:40,200
Just a baking pan with tar on it.

84
00:04:40,350 --> 00:04:42,350
Ozzak was asphalting his bed again?

85
00:04:42,750 --> 00:04:43,780
More like cooking something.

86
00:04:44,050 --> 00:04:45,650
But it won't have soaked enough yet.

87
00:04:45,750 --> 00:04:46,450
Well, try it.

88
00:05:03,950 --> 00:05:04,810
Hi, everyone.

89
00:05:06,820 --> 00:05:07,260
Hi.

90
00:05:07,440 --> 00:05:07,880
Hi.

91
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:09,740
Do you happen to have a map of Prague?

92
00:05:09,740 --> 00:05:11,520
I need to find where U Stajinek street is.

93
00:05:11,740 --> 00:05:12,960
I've never heard of it.

94
00:05:13,100 --> 00:05:14,120
It used to have a different name.

95
00:05:14,450 --> 00:05:15,550
What's supposed to be there?

96
00:05:15,850 --> 00:05:16,840
Happy Chick headquarters.

97
00:05:16,840 --> 00:05:18,680
That's the fast food place going in where the Badger was.

98
00:05:18,680 --> 00:05:21,750
I'm going to pick up my uniform and some company freebies.

99
00:05:22,550 --> 00:05:25,250
They sell fried food, schnitzels and they're on U Stajinek.

100
00:05:25,550 --> 00:05:26,450
Kinda weird.

101
00:05:26,750 --> 00:05:27,940
At least it's clear.

102
00:05:27,940 --> 00:05:30,040
Streets should be named after what's there.

103
00:05:30,040 --> 00:05:32,850
Like around the corner on Mleta, that's McDonald's headquarters.

104
00:05:33,750 --> 00:05:36,250
Nobody knew who that Anne Frank was anyway.

105
00:05:36,350 --> 00:05:38,250
U Stajinek, Prague-Libus.

106
00:05:39,150 --> 00:05:40,250
When do you start?

107
00:05:40,550 --> 00:05:43,530
Don't know, they need to convert the Badger first, they haven't even started demolishing.

108
00:05:43,530 --> 00:05:43,990
How come?

109
00:05:44,550 --> 00:05:46,550
Someone swiped the tracks off the bulldozer overnight.

110
00:05:47,750 --> 00:05:48,850
We're a nation of thieves.

111
00:05:49,060 --> 00:05:49,460
Exactly.

112
00:05:49,880 --> 00:05:51,600
That's why I'm going for the uniform myself.

113
00:05:51,860 --> 00:05:54,020
I won't risk that lady from the post office walking around in it.

114
00:05:54,670 --> 00:05:56,650
Oh, Dad, there was a slip in the mailbox.

115
00:05:56,790 --> 00:05:57,830
You've got a registered letter at the post office.

116
00:05:57,990 --> 00:05:59,150
Yeah, I'll pick it up.

117
00:05:59,290 --> 00:06:00,610
You'll need your ID for that.

118
00:06:00,670 --> 00:06:01,030
Here.

119
00:06:01,490 --> 00:06:02,210
Oh, thanks.

120
00:06:04,290 --> 00:06:05,030
Where'd you get it?

121
00:06:05,650 --> 00:06:06,480
Horvat found it.

122
00:06:06,480 --> 00:06:07,260
Where?

123
00:06:07,460 --> 00:06:08,180
At the train station.

124
00:06:09,150 --> 00:06:10,550
I haven't been there in at least a year.

125
00:06:11,180 --> 00:06:11,760
Cool.

126
00:06:12,320 --> 00:06:15,700
And this just shows how false stereotypes fool people.

127
00:06:16,080 --> 00:06:17,980
Horvat looks like a shady character.

128
00:06:18,300 --> 00:06:19,020
Shady how?

129
00:06:20,150 --> 00:06:20,660
You know, a thief.

130
00:06:20,950 --> 00:06:23,320
But he's actually a decent person.

131
00:06:23,320 --> 00:06:24,100
And warm-hearted.

132
00:06:24,750 --> 00:06:28,350
Yesterday I bumped into him on the tram and he just hugged me with joy.

133
00:06:28,950 --> 00:06:29,820
Yeah, Horvat.

134
00:06:30,050 --> 00:06:30,900
Heart on his sleeve.

135
00:06:30,900 --> 00:06:31,780
Well, bye.

136
00:06:32,280 --> 00:06:32,860
Yeah.

137
00:06:33,750 --> 00:06:34,720
How's Ozzak doing?

138
00:06:34,950 --> 00:06:35,550
Steaming.

139
00:06:36,150 --> 00:06:36,970
Oh damn.

140
00:06:37,150 --> 00:06:38,290
But he went to Marik's.

141
00:06:38,290 --> 00:06:39,730
Ah, well that's good.

142
00:06:39,830 --> 00:06:41,470
Libal, that's an old-school barman.

143
00:06:41,570 --> 00:06:43,070
He knows how to handle a regular.

144
00:06:43,190 --> 00:06:43,950
Bye then.

145
00:07:00,430 --> 00:07:00,950
Dad?

146
00:07:01,170 --> 00:07:01,430
Hmm?

147
00:07:03,150 --> 00:07:06,220
Didn't Roubalova say you lost her wallet?

148
00:07:06,220 --> 00:07:06,740
No.

149
00:07:08,850 --> 00:07:09,350
Fine.

150
00:07:11,750 --> 00:07:13,150
Do you know what a frgal is?

151
00:07:13,240 --> 00:07:13,760
Why?

152
00:07:14,250 --> 00:07:17,950
I'm reading this article and it's full of Moravian expressions.

153
00:07:18,850 --> 00:07:19,750
Is it a shoe?

154
00:07:20,650 --> 00:07:21,250
I don't know.

155
00:07:21,350 --> 00:07:22,850
Because it sounds like a boot.

156
00:07:24,150 --> 00:07:25,950
Well, could it be a pair of shoes?

157
00:07:26,050 --> 00:07:27,750
More likely some kind of cheese.

158
00:07:30,050 --> 00:07:31,350
Wake up Ozzak.

159
00:07:35,350 --> 00:07:36,250
Or a nose?

160
00:07:37,450 --> 00:07:39,350
No, that's dumb too.

161
00:07:42,750 --> 00:07:44,050
Were those twelves?

162
00:07:44,300 --> 00:07:44,820
Yeah.

163
00:07:47,050 --> 00:07:48,950
Ghosts, or what?

164
00:07:51,450 --> 00:07:54,080
Jozko, I thought I'd never see you again.

165
00:07:54,080 --> 00:07:55,220
What happened?

166
00:07:55,480 --> 00:07:56,220
I was kidnapped!

167
00:07:56,650 --> 00:07:58,750
Jesus Christ, do they want a ransom?

168
00:07:58,760 --> 00:07:59,640
He's here now, right?

169
00:08:00,280 --> 00:08:01,540
Thank God.

170
00:08:02,850 --> 00:08:03,600
We've got you.

171
00:08:05,450 --> 00:08:06,050
And who kidnapped you?

172
00:08:06,340 --> 00:08:07,100
I don't know.

173
00:08:07,640 --> 00:08:09,280
A man, a woman, and some kind of dwarf.

174
00:08:09,300 --> 00:08:10,400
Right from this room.

175
00:08:10,520 --> 00:08:12,560
I don't know what they did to me, but I woke up in the bushes.

176
00:08:13,150 --> 00:08:14,700
Uncle, that's really weird.

177
00:08:15,250 --> 00:08:16,720
And you two didn't hear anything.

178
00:08:17,050 --> 00:08:19,050
That dwarf was screaming bloody murder.

179
00:08:20,250 --> 00:08:22,750
Ozzak, how was it at Marik's yesterday?

180
00:08:24,150 --> 00:08:24,750
Epic.

181
00:08:25,150 --> 00:08:28,250
Did you know Husten started making Magicke Oko in kegs?

182
00:08:30,070 --> 00:08:30,570
Right.

183
00:08:31,250 --> 00:08:32,750
Well, the main thing is you're home.

184
00:08:34,050 --> 00:08:35,450
I made myself some coffee last night.

185
00:08:37,400 --> 00:08:37,980
Want some?

186
00:08:51,690 --> 00:08:52,190
Jaromir.

187
00:08:57,950 --> 00:08:59,350
Something from the old days.

188
00:08:59,840 --> 00:09:01,200
Playing the keyboards, huh.

189
00:09:01,280 --> 00:09:02,780
Ah, I know, I'm setting up the gear.

190
00:09:03,650 --> 00:09:05,750
Are these still the ones from Karl-Marx-Stadt?

191
00:09:08,250 --> 00:09:08,850
They are.

192
00:09:10,750 --> 00:09:12,350
Nothing beats the original sound.

193
00:09:13,050 --> 00:09:14,550
But they have more memory, right?

194
00:09:15,050 --> 00:09:16,850
4 songs and Lohengrin.

195
00:09:20,520 --> 00:09:21,080
Tomas!

196
00:09:21,500 --> 00:09:22,820
Marcelka, it's here, let's go.

197
00:09:23,240 --> 00:09:25,560
Allow me to introduce, this is Jaromir Simara.

198
00:09:25,760 --> 00:09:27,560
We used to play together for Frantisek Janecek.

199
00:09:29,050 --> 00:09:30,350
We've already met.

200
00:09:32,880 --> 00:09:36,160
We were just talking with Jaromir about his keyboards.

201
00:09:36,220 --> 00:09:39,100
Mr. Simara was saying they were very expensive in their day.

202
00:09:40,050 --> 00:09:44,850
I wanted to suggest to Jaromir that we program a new song into them.

203
00:09:45,350 --> 00:09:46,850
What new song?

204
00:09:47,080 --> 00:09:48,600
Four songs and Lohengrin.

205
00:09:48,600 --> 00:09:52,600
Well, I wrote a new special song for Lidecko.

206
00:09:53,050 --> 00:09:55,950
So the people of Lidecko know I care about them.

207
00:09:58,250 --> 00:10:00,050
I'll play it for you on guitar.

208
00:10:00,950 --> 00:10:02,790
And what if we then put it into the keyboards?

209
00:10:02,790 --> 00:10:04,170
Maybe in place of Lohengrin.

210
00:10:04,410 --> 00:10:05,310
Lohengrin pays my bills.

211
00:10:07,950 --> 00:10:08,450
Bro!

212
00:10:08,670 --> 00:10:09,590
Bro, where are you?

213
00:10:09,650 --> 00:10:10,050
We're leaving.

214
00:10:10,270 --> 00:10:10,910
It's them.

215
00:10:11,940 --> 00:10:12,380
Who?

216
00:10:13,350 --> 00:10:14,390
The ones who kidnapped me.

217
00:10:14,390 --> 00:10:15,210
You were kidnapped?

218
00:10:15,210 --> 00:10:18,850
I thought it might help the police with the identification.

219
00:10:19,950 --> 00:10:22,350
Did you say one of them was shorter?

220
00:10:24,550 --> 00:10:25,150
Yeah, this one.

221
00:10:25,960 --> 00:10:26,940
He just came out bigger.

222
00:10:30,850 --> 00:10:34,370
Alright, so on the way to the concert we'll stop by the police.

223
00:10:34,370 --> 00:10:35,390
You know, Marcelka.

224
00:10:35,590 --> 00:10:36,330
And they'll!

225
00:10:36,820 --> 00:10:38,260
Look into it.

226
00:10:38,360 --> 00:10:39,000
Thanks, bro.

227
00:10:41,150 --> 00:10:43,410
Are we going by train?

228
00:10:43,650 --> 00:10:44,250
Just like that?

229
00:10:48,350 --> 00:10:50,460
Mr. Simara, don't you want help?

230
00:10:50,460 --> 00:10:50,600
No.

231
00:10:51,650 --> 00:10:55,050
I carry everything myself so I know I have everything.

232
00:11:09,050 --> 00:11:12,950
I still think the Lidecko people would enjoy that song.

233
00:11:13,850 --> 00:11:17,550
Your people will be happiest hearing what they already know.

234
00:11:17,950 --> 00:11:20,150
People are scared of new things, especially in the countryside.

235
00:11:21,220 --> 00:11:22,260
Turn right there.

236
00:11:22,360 --> 00:11:22,620
Where?

237
00:11:24,290 --> 00:11:24,850
There.

238
00:11:25,420 --> 00:11:26,000
Oh, there.

239
00:11:29,450 --> 00:11:33,350
Mr. Simara, if we switched seats, I could navigate better.

240
00:11:35,150 --> 00:11:37,150
Jaromir gets carsick in the back.

241
00:11:38,950 --> 00:11:40,450
At least, unless things have changed.

242
00:11:43,150 --> 00:11:46,540
Couldn't you at least put the organ on the roof so I can see ahead?

243
00:11:46,540 --> 00:11:46,620
No.

244
00:11:49,250 --> 00:11:51,350
Take it easy, let's get there in one piece.

245
00:11:51,590 --> 00:11:52,690
You missed the turn.

246
00:11:52,870 --> 00:11:53,230
Damn.

247
00:12:05,750 --> 00:12:06,850
Hey, Iva, how are you?

248
00:12:07,450 --> 00:12:08,160
I'm ironing.

249
00:12:08,350 --> 00:12:09,650
You've got it good.

250
00:12:11,850 --> 00:12:14,110
I'm bringing back the map, Mom says thanks a lot.

251
00:12:14,550 --> 00:12:15,750
Yeah, just toss it on the table.

252
00:12:20,930 --> 00:12:21,510
What is it?

253
00:12:22,650 --> 00:12:26,580
You won't mind that I drew Mom's route to Libus and back on it, will you?

254
00:12:26,850 --> 00:12:28,750
No, that won't bother us.

255
00:12:32,950 --> 00:12:33,660
What's going on?

256
00:12:34,050 --> 00:12:36,750
You won't mind that I drew a few more routes on it?

257
00:12:36,850 --> 00:12:37,550
What kind?

258
00:12:38,040 --> 00:12:38,500
Various.

259
00:12:42,650 --> 00:12:45,050
I was having fun, so I got a little carried away.

260
00:12:47,450 --> 00:12:49,250
And why is some of it in red and some in green?

261
00:12:49,650 --> 00:12:51,050
It's by type of transportation.

262
00:12:52,720 --> 00:12:56,220
The route from home to school is in green because you can comfortably walk there.

263
00:12:56,460 --> 00:12:58,740
The route to the Badger too, and to the post office too.

264
00:12:59,340 --> 00:13:03,400
The route to the Happy Chick headquarters is in red because the fastest way is by metro.

265
00:13:03,720 --> 00:13:07,760
And the routes best reached by surface transport are marked in blue.

266
00:13:07,840 --> 00:13:08,980
And you know what I found out?

267
00:13:09,080 --> 00:13:09,220
No.

268
00:13:09,750 --> 00:13:12,850
If we didn't go to school through the park, it would be quicker.

269
00:13:12,950 --> 00:13:14,640
Check out the yellow one.

270
00:13:14,750 --> 00:13:17,540
If we turned onto Beda Travnicek street and went through Levna...

271
00:13:17,540 --> 00:13:18,240
Which one is Levna?

272
00:13:18,550 --> 00:13:19,720
Where the Lidl is.

273
00:13:19,720 --> 00:13:20,040
Ah.

274
00:13:20,550 --> 00:13:22,850
We'd be at school three minutes earlier.

275
00:13:24,850 --> 00:13:25,850
That'd be great.

276
00:13:27,350 --> 00:13:28,750
And you really aren't mad?

277
00:13:29,250 --> 00:13:32,280
I tried to erase it, but I accidentally erased the Rudolfinum.

278
00:13:32,550 --> 00:13:33,680
She's crazy.

279
00:13:33,850 --> 00:13:36,050
I'm glad it's so nice and clear now.

280
00:13:38,950 --> 00:13:42,250
Could I doodle some more? I thought of more routes.

281
00:13:50,750 --> 00:13:54,250
It wasn't a huge success, but it wasn't a loss either.

282
00:13:59,950 --> 00:14:02,050
Marcelka, how did it look from the audience?

283
00:14:05,050 --> 00:14:06,650
It definitely wasn't a loss.

284
00:14:07,350 --> 00:14:08,450
But it takes getting used to.

285
00:14:09,050 --> 00:14:12,140
I completely forgot how demanding performing in front of people is.

286
00:14:12,250 --> 00:14:13,750
You recovered well.

287
00:14:14,550 --> 00:14:16,850
Even that unfortunate glitch with Lohengrin.

288
00:14:17,150 --> 00:14:20,050
Well, that used to happen to Jaromir before too.

289
00:14:22,550 --> 00:14:24,760
Those buttons are too tiny for you, right, Jaromir?

290
00:14:24,760 --> 00:14:25,240
Tiny?

291
00:14:25,850 --> 00:14:28,450
I couldn't see them, the work light wasn't on.

292
00:14:28,550 --> 00:14:30,450
Terrible chaos, awful gig.

293
00:14:30,950 --> 00:14:31,980
Turn left there.

294
00:14:32,350 --> 00:14:34,840
And their sound guy was quite unpleasant too.

295
00:14:35,250 --> 00:14:38,720
The way he checked our arrival, every extension cord, I've never seen that before.

296
00:14:38,720 --> 00:14:39,200
Me neither.

297
00:14:41,450 --> 00:14:42,150
On to the next one then.

298
00:14:42,950 --> 00:14:45,000
How did those two extension cords get tangled with ours?

299
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:45,480
No idea.

300
00:14:47,650 --> 00:14:49,350
Weren't we supposed to turn left somewhere here?

301
00:14:50,470 --> 00:14:51,510
I said so.

302
00:14:51,710 --> 00:14:52,690
I didn't hear anything.

303
00:14:52,890 --> 00:14:53,650
Me neither.

304
00:14:54,450 --> 00:14:58,450
If I could sit up front, we wouldn't have to detour through Nasavrky now.

305
00:14:58,450 --> 00:15:00,670
I'll turn around, it won't delay us much.

306
00:15:00,830 --> 00:15:03,610
If you had a highway sticker, we could be home by now.

307
00:15:03,870 --> 00:15:04,770
A highway sticker?

308
00:15:04,950 --> 00:15:06,990
A highway sticker is a ticket to the slaughterhouse.

309
00:15:07,550 --> 00:15:09,450
If we were in Germany, I wouldn't say a word.

310
00:15:09,610 --> 00:15:13,350
But for our occasional driving around here, it's a waste of money.

311
00:15:13,550 --> 00:15:16,090
Look, Kolin, 22 kilometers, we're almost home.

312
00:15:18,510 --> 00:15:19,230
Got it for me?

313
00:15:20,050 --> 00:15:24,630
Once the Lidecko people say it was actually a good concert, maybe more will come next time.

314
00:15:24,630 --> 00:15:25,590
What do you think, Marcelka?

315
00:15:26,650 --> 00:15:27,550
We can try.

316
00:15:27,850 --> 00:15:28,850
In a few weeks.

317
00:15:29,550 --> 00:15:30,250
Right away.

318
00:15:31,150 --> 00:15:32,450
I left my drums there.

319
00:15:48,050 --> 00:15:51,450
Iva, do you know what time it is?

320
00:15:57,550 --> 00:15:58,450
Good evening.

321
00:15:58,490 --> 00:15:59,250
Good evening.

322
00:16:00,750 --> 00:16:01,950
This is Mrs. Vesela.

323
00:16:02,050 --> 00:16:03,700
Nice to meet you, who are you?

324
00:16:03,850 --> 00:16:09,380
Sorry for falling asleep here, but little Venousek has been sleeping terribly and it was so quiet here.

325
00:16:09,380 --> 00:16:11,580
Mrs. Vesela came to tell us that Ozzak is sleeping at their place.

326
00:16:12,450 --> 00:16:13,350
With Venousek.

327
00:16:15,150 --> 00:16:16,750
Venousek is our little boy.

328
00:16:17,450 --> 00:16:20,750
Please, how did Ozzak get to your place?

329
00:16:22,250 --> 00:16:25,250
He rang the bell, said, hi, Ivushka.

330
00:16:25,350 --> 00:16:29,950
And went straight to sleep on the doggy bed.

331
00:16:30,750 --> 00:16:31,550
Same as yesterday.

332
00:16:33,950 --> 00:16:35,920
Venousek has stuffed animals under his crib.

333
00:16:35,920 --> 00:16:36,960
He's afraid of them at night.

334
00:16:39,240 --> 00:16:42,340
Mrs. Vesela, I'm terribly sorry about my brother.

335
00:16:42,380 --> 00:16:44,200
No, please, don't apologize.

336
00:16:44,690 --> 00:16:45,230
Don't apologize.

337
00:16:45,650 --> 00:16:47,850
It's me who should apologize for yesterday.

338
00:16:47,950 --> 00:16:50,450
We shouldn't have carried him out onto the street.

339
00:16:50,850 --> 00:16:53,450
But we didn't know him well enough yet.

340
00:16:53,950 --> 00:16:56,090
We thought he was homeless.

341
00:16:56,450 --> 00:17:02,550
But today his ID fell out of his pocket, so I came to tell you where he is, so you wouldn't worry.

342
00:17:04,110 --> 00:17:06,010
No, this is inexcusable.

343
00:17:06,010 --> 00:17:08,950
I promise this won't happen again.

344
00:17:09,030 --> 00:17:10,170
Come, I have the car downstairs.

345
00:17:10,170 --> 00:17:13,750
Actually, I came to ask if it could wait until morning.

346
00:17:14,320 --> 00:17:14,720
What?

347
00:17:15,950 --> 00:17:17,450
Because of Venousek.

348
00:17:17,650 --> 00:17:19,550
He's teething.

349
00:17:19,750 --> 00:17:25,130
When Mr. Ozzak came yesterday, Venousek fell asleep for the first time in three days.

350
00:17:25,130 --> 00:17:26,530
And again today.

351
00:17:27,550 --> 00:17:30,060
You know, my husband needs his sleep too.

352
00:17:30,060 --> 00:17:31,220
He's a pilot.

353
00:17:33,550 --> 00:17:35,750
You could pick him up first thing in the morning.

354
00:17:36,850 --> 00:17:38,050
Here's my card.

355
00:17:40,350 --> 00:17:45,330
Mrs. Vesela, my brother is obviously not in control of himself.

356
00:17:45,330 --> 00:17:45,850
You understand?

357
00:17:46,850 --> 00:17:48,350
Come, we'll go right now.

358
00:18:02,350 --> 00:18:03,560
Can't you put this away?

359
00:18:03,850 --> 00:18:05,900
No, because I haven't finished vacuuming yet.

360
00:18:06,250 --> 00:18:09,440
So put it away now and take it out again when you vacuum, okay?

361
00:18:09,650 --> 00:18:11,280
You know what, vacuum yourself.

362
00:18:11,280 --> 00:18:12,180
I have to go to school.

363
00:18:14,950 --> 00:18:16,150
Bro, thanks.

364
00:18:16,650 --> 00:18:17,350
Thank you.

365
00:18:18,850 --> 00:18:20,470
Ozzak, let go of me.

366
00:18:20,930 --> 00:18:22,210
Ivushka, your dad is a hero.

367
00:18:22,350 --> 00:18:23,730
He saved me from three kidnappers.

368
00:18:23,830 --> 00:18:24,790
They got me again.

369
00:18:26,890 --> 00:18:28,950
Ozzak, for God's sake, snap out of it...

370
00:18:28,950 --> 00:18:31,330
You're becoming genuinely dangerous.

371
00:18:31,470 --> 00:18:31,770
Me?

372
00:18:32,490 --> 00:18:33,830
The dwarf is the dangerous one.

373
00:18:34,220 --> 00:18:35,340
And it's good that you fought for me.

374
00:18:36,750 --> 00:18:38,350
That was little Venousek Vesely.

375
00:18:38,390 --> 00:18:40,940
And you basically broke into the Veselys' place.

376
00:18:41,100 --> 00:18:43,700
You're lucky they didn't call the cops on you.

377
00:18:43,820 --> 00:18:44,720
That wasn't a dwarf?

378
00:18:48,650 --> 00:18:50,990
So right now you're going to go to the shop and open up.

379
00:18:51,250 --> 00:18:54,450
And when you get back, you're going to vacuum, so you actually help out around here.

380
00:18:54,450 --> 00:18:56,770
Wait, today is the beer pentathlon qualifier at Marik's.

381
00:18:56,770 --> 00:19:01,250
You're done with Marik's until you learn how to come home.

382
00:19:02,050 --> 00:19:04,250
I really don't know what to do with you people.

383
00:19:04,650 --> 00:19:06,150
Wait, what do you mean "you people"?

384
00:19:07,350 --> 00:19:09,440
How do I explain to you that things are hard for me right now?

385
00:19:09,850 --> 00:19:11,650
Is it that hard to help me out a little?

386
00:19:12,050 --> 00:19:13,020
And who's going to help me?

387
00:19:13,350 --> 00:19:15,800
While you're touring cultural centers with Marcelka, you don't lift a finger at home.

388
00:19:16,050 --> 00:19:18,050
I can't even pick up a stupid registered letter.

389
00:19:18,220 --> 00:19:19,720
Well, let Ozzak help her then.

390
00:19:19,940 --> 00:19:21,320
Sure, because I have it so easy, right?

391
00:19:23,250 --> 00:19:24,350
Let Ozzak do everything.

392
00:19:30,750 --> 00:19:31,950
I'm sorry, okay.

393
00:19:32,450 --> 00:19:33,550
It's just a lot right now.

394
00:19:35,450 --> 00:19:37,450
Yeah, I brought you a frgal, want some?

395
00:19:37,950 --> 00:19:39,660
I'm more in the mood for something sweet.

396
00:19:39,660 --> 00:19:40,100
Well, wait.

397
00:19:40,480 --> 00:19:41,780
It is sweet, try it.

398
00:19:43,050 --> 00:19:43,490
Oh.

399
00:19:45,650 --> 00:19:48,050
Yeah, where's the slip for that registered letter?

400
00:19:48,350 --> 00:19:49,250
I already went.

401
00:19:52,330 --> 00:19:52,850
Wait.

402
00:19:53,850 --> 00:19:55,550
How did they give it to you?

403
00:19:55,850 --> 00:19:59,550
I took your cap, your ID, and called the lady at the window "postal angel."

404
00:20:01,950 --> 00:20:03,050
Nobody noticed a thing.

405
00:20:04,030 --> 00:20:04,550
Obviously.

406
00:20:05,950 --> 00:20:06,710
What is it?

407
00:20:12,150 --> 00:20:15,950
I've become a VIP member of the United Recycling Centers.

408
00:20:16,090 --> 00:20:16,770
How?

409
00:20:18,050 --> 00:20:18,750
I don't know.

410
00:20:19,650 --> 00:20:22,450
They say I've turned in one and a half tons of iron.

411
00:20:23,650 --> 00:20:24,950
That's gotta be a mistake, right?

412
00:20:25,610 --> 00:20:26,190
Probably.

413
00:20:27,750 --> 00:20:29,350
But there are perks included.

414
00:20:29,750 --> 00:20:30,850
Like some discounts?

415
00:20:30,950 --> 00:20:34,050
Free soup and a shower with every visit.

416
00:20:44,950 --> 00:20:46,780
Marcelka, it's about time you got here.

417
00:20:46,950 --> 00:20:47,950
I have a song.

418
00:20:49,250 --> 00:20:50,350
That's wonderful.

419
00:20:50,750 --> 00:20:53,550
I'll read you the lyrics, listen.

420
00:20:54,550 --> 00:20:57,850
My goddess from Chropin.

421
00:20:58,350 --> 00:21:01,210
For your eyes I think of no other.

422
00:21:02,150 --> 00:21:07,950
In Kojetin nor Hulin are there girls like you, Chropin.

423
00:21:11,550 --> 00:21:15,950
There's a lot of feeling in it, Tomas, but it sounds a bit clunky.

424
00:21:15,950 --> 00:21:17,750
I think it'll work on the Chropin folks.

425
00:21:19,650 --> 00:21:20,640
And what about Mr. Simara?

426
00:21:20,850 --> 00:21:24,150
Will he want to erase something from the memory for this?

427
00:21:24,950 --> 00:21:26,250
That's the best part.

428
00:21:26,850 --> 00:21:28,550
It can be sung to the Lohengrin melody.

429
00:21:42,530 --> 00:21:42,970
No.

430
00:21:44,250 --> 00:21:46,770
What if I marked the whole way from Marik's to here?

431
00:21:46,770 --> 00:21:47,090
No.

432
00:21:47,550 --> 00:21:48,750
Marcelka, let's go.

433
00:21:48,950 --> 00:21:50,270
Younger siblings are pigs.

434
00:21:50,270 --> 00:21:50,870
Excuse me.

435
00:21:51,550 --> 00:21:52,550
Are you a younger sibling?

436
00:21:52,550 --> 00:21:52,710
No.

437
00:21:53,150 --> 00:21:54,350
I said it on your behalf.

438
00:21:55,330 --> 00:21:55,770
What for.

439
00:21:55,970 --> 00:21:56,350
No.

440
00:21:56,910 --> 00:22:00,370
Yeah, Jaromir, no, just sit down for a moment, I'll grab the stuff from the back.

441
00:22:00,450 --> 00:22:02,050
Take it easy, no chaos.

442
00:22:02,170 --> 00:22:02,530
Right, right.

443
00:22:02,630 --> 00:22:04,990
What if I strung a piece of twine from doorknob to doorknob?

444
00:22:05,230 --> 00:22:05,670
No!

445
00:22:07,740 --> 00:22:08,680
Hi, everyone.

446
00:22:09,850 --> 00:22:13,060
I wouldn't have come, but the kid kept insisting you have to see this.

447
00:22:13,150 --> 00:22:13,860
Mom, but I...

448
00:22:13,860 --> 00:22:14,140
Shut it.

449
00:22:15,880 --> 00:22:17,200
You look like a different person.

450
00:22:17,320 --> 00:22:19,040
They say uniforms suit me.

451
00:22:19,280 --> 00:22:20,380
Well, Simona.

452
00:22:20,900 --> 00:22:24,120
This is the first employer who actually cares that I'm dressed.

453
00:22:24,340 --> 00:22:25,620
Mom, can I take off the cap?

454
00:22:25,780 --> 00:22:25,800
No.

455
00:22:25,940 --> 00:22:27,340
What if I made a deal with Lexa?

456
00:22:27,480 --> 00:22:27,920
No.

457
00:22:29,610 --> 00:22:30,890
No, sit down for a moment.

458
00:22:31,310 --> 00:22:33,290
Listen, I have an improvement for the Chropin song.

459
00:22:33,410 --> 00:22:34,450
I think you'll like it.

460
00:22:34,530 --> 00:22:36,090
Tomas, how come you haven't even introduced us?

461
00:22:36,390 --> 00:22:37,230
Oh, right.

462
00:22:37,950 --> 00:22:40,230
Simona, neighbor... Simara, Jaromir.

463
00:22:40,490 --> 00:22:40,850
Simona.

464
00:22:41,270 --> 00:22:41,970
Lexa, her son.

465
00:22:42,090 --> 00:22:42,230
Come.

466
00:22:42,510 --> 00:22:42,870
Bucek.

467
00:22:43,390 --> 00:22:44,450
You're standing on my extension cord.

468
00:22:45,010 --> 00:22:46,210
You're standing on my extension cord.

469
00:22:46,950 --> 00:22:49,270
What if Ivushka walked me home?

470
00:22:49,270 --> 00:22:49,630
No.

471
00:22:50,750 --> 00:22:52,080
Yeah, Jaromir, please.

472
00:22:52,080 --> 00:22:54,100
About that Chropin song, I wrote a new one.

473
00:22:54,180 --> 00:22:54,600
Well, bye then.

474
00:22:54,740 --> 00:22:55,620
Yeah, yeah, bye, see you.

475
00:22:55,620 --> 00:22:57,360
Simona, come on, tell him something.

476
00:22:57,640 --> 00:22:58,680
Look, sort it out yourself.

477
00:22:58,780 --> 00:23:00,780
At my place you were never so hammered you couldn't find your way home.

478
00:23:01,040 --> 00:23:01,440
Hammered?

479
00:23:01,960 --> 00:23:02,360
Simona.

480
00:23:02,500 --> 00:23:02,840
Yeah.

481
00:23:03,040 --> 00:23:04,260
This thing came for scrap.

482
00:23:04,480 --> 00:23:05,320
Know anything about it?

483
00:23:05,500 --> 00:23:07,020
Yeah, Horvat mentioned, I'll pick it up.

484
00:23:07,220 --> 00:23:07,620
Thank you.

485
00:23:07,780 --> 00:23:08,400
Pick up how?

486
00:23:09,250 --> 00:23:11,820
You know how hard he worked on it, and you won't even let him shower.

487
00:23:11,820 --> 00:23:12,220
But...

488
00:23:12,750 --> 00:23:14,420
Mom, can I take off the cap now?

489
00:23:14,420 --> 00:23:14,560
Yeah.

490
00:23:15,350 --> 00:23:16,250
We need to go.

491
00:23:16,350 --> 00:23:18,280
Right, no chaos please.

492
00:23:18,550 --> 00:23:19,250
What if I went to Marik's...

493
00:23:21,350 --> 00:23:22,150
And didn't drink.

494
00:23:23,730 --> 00:23:24,250
No.

495
00:23:24,650 --> 00:23:33,810
When, where?

496
00:23:33,810 --> 00:23:35,620
You missed it again.

497
00:23:35,620 --> 00:23:37,950
Oh God, we don't have any time at all.

498
00:23:37,960 --> 00:23:39,500
Because you call it out too late.

499
00:23:39,660 --> 00:23:42,480
I call it out on time, but you drive too fast.

500
00:23:42,600 --> 00:23:45,240
Because you keep telling me we don't have much time.

501
00:23:45,320 --> 00:23:48,040
We don't have time because you keep missing the turns.

502
00:23:49,050 --> 00:23:50,950
Your sound check is in ten minutes.

503
00:23:51,850 --> 00:23:52,590
We'll make it.

504
00:23:52,750 --> 00:23:54,750
Jaromir can connect the amps quickly.

505
00:23:55,450 --> 00:23:57,550
It'll be faster to go through Troubky.

506
00:23:57,860 --> 00:23:58,380
Troubky?

507
00:23:58,560 --> 00:23:58,820
Yeah.

508
00:23:59,350 --> 00:24:00,850
But the Germans burned that down, didn't they?

509
00:24:03,990 --> 00:24:04,390
Good grief.

510
00:24:04,850 --> 00:24:06,850
Jaromir, that was ages ago.

511
00:24:07,650 --> 00:24:08,850
I don't have the baritone sax.

512
00:24:10,590 --> 00:24:11,450
Oh God, how?

513
00:24:11,970 --> 00:24:12,370
Damn!

514
00:24:13,850 --> 00:24:16,550
That shop was such a mess again!

515
00:24:18,250 --> 00:24:20,050
Could we go back?

516
00:24:21,150 --> 00:24:22,250
We're in Chropin.

517
00:24:34,350 --> 00:24:35,930
Yeah, thanks, you're really sweet.

518
00:24:35,930 --> 00:24:39,310
And since I was already helping, I also washed the baking pan with the coffee.

519
00:24:39,470 --> 00:24:40,230
How did you manage that?

520
00:24:40,450 --> 00:24:41,710
I put everything on ninety degrees.

521
00:24:42,230 --> 00:24:43,530
Now everything's brown, you know.

522
00:24:46,450 --> 00:24:48,450
And weird, it doesn't look like it even shrunk.

523
00:24:52,290 --> 00:24:53,450
So this is the price tag.

524
00:24:53,450 --> 00:24:55,670
Well, since I helped you, can I go to Marik's?

525
00:24:55,950 --> 00:24:56,550
No, and stop helping me.

526
00:24:59,350 --> 00:25:03,460
Well, Iva, I figured out why Mr. Ozzak goes to the Veselys'.

527
00:25:03,460 --> 00:25:03,900
Why?

528
00:25:04,350 --> 00:25:05,450
Because he's going home.

529
00:25:05,640 --> 00:25:06,700
That's ridiculous.

530
00:25:06,940 --> 00:25:07,200
It's not.

531
00:25:07,750 --> 00:25:13,320
Look, here's Marik's place.

532
00:25:13,750 --> 00:25:16,360
And this is Bifidus Aktiv street, where Mrs. Vesela lives.

533
00:25:16,750 --> 00:25:19,150
And this is the Badger.

534
00:25:19,850 --> 00:25:20,810
And here's where you live.

535
00:25:21,150 --> 00:25:21,950
Wow, same route.

536
00:25:23,750 --> 00:25:27,750
So I think someone should go with Mr. Ozzak from the restaurant today on his way back.

537
00:25:27,950 --> 00:25:28,760
Right.

538
00:25:29,250 --> 00:25:30,350
And drive him home.

539
00:25:30,750 --> 00:25:31,940
Well, that's option one.

540
00:25:32,150 --> 00:25:33,000
And option two?

541
00:25:33,250 --> 00:25:35,450
Drive him to the Badger, because from there he can find the way.

542
00:25:37,650 --> 00:25:40,060
I think Mr. Ozzak will go with option three.

543
00:25:40,450 --> 00:25:41,350
He'll vacuum.

544
00:25:42,950 --> 00:25:44,150
Well, do I have a choice?

545
00:25:59,250 --> 00:26:13,950
Howdy, y'all. Recently in Gottwal... in Zlin, I felt that as a Prague guy, I wasn't welcome in beautiful Moravia.

546
00:26:14,850 --> 00:26:19,650
But, as they say where you're from, time will tell.

547
00:26:48,590 --> 00:26:50,710
There are no girls.

548
00:26:50,710 --> 00:26:53,980
Like you, Chropin.

549
00:27:02,950 --> 00:27:03,950
Thanks, y'all!
